&gt;
&gt; &gt; A Growing Problem
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; The typical way of handling test cases in JUnit is to create a class
&gt; &gt; with methods beginning with &quot;test&quot;. For example, we could create the
&gt; &gt; methods testNullAccount() and testEmptyAccount() to handle cases where
&gt; &gt; the account object is null and empty, respectively. This approach is
&gt; &gt; satisfactory for a few test cases, but what if the number of test cases
&gt; &gt; grows to 50 or even 500? It seems that there is always another test case
&gt; &gt; I should test for. Having this many methods becomes unmanageable. The
&gt; &gt; situation gets ugly.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; You might work around this limitation by placing all test cases and
&gt; &gt; assert statements sequentially inside a single method. This approach
&gt; &gt; suffers from two limitations. The first limitation is the need to
&gt; &gt; replicate the test code for every test case. Even if you have only two
&gt; &gt; or three lines of code per test case, the size of the method will
&gt; &gt; mushroom and become hard to maintain (and read). See example below (
&gt; &gt; Taken from JavaPro ) -
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; public void testCreateBatchLabelNoInnerClass() {
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;    try {
&gt; &gt;       BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt; &gt;          &quot;20010530&quot;,  &quot;A13&quot;,  &quot;1&quot; );
&gt; &gt;       assert ( aBatchLabel.getBatchLabel().equals(
&gt; &gt;          &quot;A13-1 EXP. 05/01&quot; ) ) ;
&gt; &gt;    } catch (Exception e) {
&gt; &gt;       assert ( &quot;Exception:&quot; + e, false );
&gt; &gt;    }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;    try {
&gt; &gt;       BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt; &gt;          &quot;20010530&quot;,  &quot;A13&quot;,  &quot;&quot; );
&gt; &gt;       assert ( aBatchLabel.getBatchLabel().equals(
&gt; &gt;          &quot;A13 EXP. 05/01&quot; ) ) ;
&gt; &gt;    } catch (Exception e) {
&gt; &gt;       assert ( &quot;Exception:&quot; + e, false );
&gt; &gt;    }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;    try {
&gt; &gt;       BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt; &gt;          &quot;20011231&quot;,  &quot;A13&quot;,  &quot;1&quot; );
&gt; &gt;       assert ( aBatchLabel.getBatchLabel().equals(
&gt; &gt;          &quot;A13-1 EXP. 12/01&quot; ) ) ;
&gt; &gt;    } catch (Exception e) {
&gt; &gt;       assert ( &quot;Exception:&quot; + e, false );
&gt; &gt;    }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;    try {
&gt; &gt;       BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt; &gt;          &quot;20010101&quot;,  &quot;A13&quot;,  &quot;1&quot; );
&gt; &gt;       assert ( aBatchLabel.getBatchLabel().equals(
&gt; &gt;          &quot;A13-1 EXP. 01/01&quot; ) ) ;
&gt; &gt;    } catch (Exception e) {
&gt; &gt;       assert ( &quot;Exception:&quot; + e, false );
&gt; &gt;    }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;    try {
&gt; &gt;       BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt; &gt;          &quot;20010101&quot;,  &quot;A123&quot;, &quot;99&quot; );
&gt; &gt;       assert ( aBatchLabel.getBatchLabel().equals(
&gt; &gt;          &quot;A123-99 EXP. 01/01&quot; ) ) ;
&gt; &gt;    } catch (Exception e) {
&gt; &gt;       assert ( &quot;Exception:&quot; + e, false );
&gt; &gt;    }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;    try {
&gt; &gt;       BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt; &gt;          &quot;2001530&quot;,   &quot;A999&quot;, &quot;&quot; );
&gt; &gt;    } catch (Exception e) {
&gt; &gt;       assert( &quot;Wrong Exception thrown: &quot; + e,
&gt; &gt;          e.getClass().equals(
&gt; &gt;          BadDateException.class )) ;
&gt; &gt;    }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;    try {
&gt; &gt;       BatchLabel aBatchLabel = new BatchLabel(
&gt; &gt;          &quot;20010530&quot;,   &quot;913&quot;, &quot;1&quot; );
&gt; &gt;    } catch (Exception e) {
&gt; &gt;       assert( &quot;Wrong Exception thrown: &quot; + e,
&gt; &gt;          e.getClass().equals(
&gt; &gt;          BadLotException.class )) ;
&gt; &gt;    }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt;    // etc
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; }
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; The second limitation is that JUnit will stop the testing after the
&gt; &gt; first failure?the remaining test cases won&#39;t be executed.
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; What can be the solution on these two limitations?
&gt; &gt;
